altered form of this), a habitational name for someone from Burgundy (Old French <i>Bourgogne</i>), a region of eastern France having Dijon as its center. The area was invaded by the <i>Burgundii</i>, an ancient Germanic tribe from whom it takes its name, in about  AD  480. The duchy of Burgundy, created in 877 by Charles II, King of the Western Franks, was extremely powerful in the later Middle Ages, especially under Philip the Bold (1342–1404; duke from 1363). Compare   Bourgoyne   and   Bourguignon  ."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]},{"name":"Ela","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Apparently an altered form of <b>Hilda</b> , not in use before the 20th century."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Alice Ela Bourgogne was born in 1090, in Ellington, Huntingdonshire, England, United Kingdom. She married Hugh de Segrave in 1113, in Seagrave, Leicestershire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1194, at the age of 104."},"et":{"1090–1194":"1090–1194","1089–1133":"1089–1133","1114–1166":"1114–1166","1090":"1090","1114":"1114","1113":"1113","1133":"1133","